# EduPod Regulatory Portal — Comprehensive Plan

> **Purpose**: Research-backed plan for a unified Regulatory Portal covering every statutory, compliance and governance obligation Irish schools face. This document is the result of deep research into Irish education law, DES requirements, regulatory bodies, and competitor analysis (VSware, Compass, Aladdin).

---

## Executive Summary

Irish schools navigate a complex web of statutory reporting, regulatory compliance, and governance obligations across **at least 14 distinct regulatory domains**. Currently, schools piece together compliance across spreadsheets, portal logins, and ad-hoc processes. EduPod's Regulatory Portal will be the **single pane of glass** that transforms compliance from a burden into a managed, automated workflow — and become the strongest differentiator in the Irish market.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This is a research and planning document. No code changes are proposed at this stage. The next step is to review this plan, prioritise domains, and then create implementation specs for each.

---

## Part 1: Regulatory Landscape — The Full Picture

### 1.1 Statutory Data Returns to the Department of Education

#### A. September Returns (Post-Primary) — Files A–E + Form TL

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **Legal basis** | Education Act 1998, DES Circular |
| **Who** | All post-primary schools |
| **When** | Annually in September/October |
| **What** | Five encrypted data files (A, B, C, D, E) covering staff deployment, classes, subjects, student enrolment. Form TL summarises teacher hours per subject per week |
| **How** | Files generated by school management software → encrypted automatically → uploaded to DES portal. Files must NOT be opened after generation (corrupts encryption) |
| **Impact** | Determines teacher allocation, capitation grants, funding |

**Files breakdown:**
- **File A**: Staff data — teacher qualifications, employment type, hours
- **File B**: Requires additional preparation (supplementary data)
- **File C**: Class/group data — class sizes, year groups
- **File D**: Subject data — subject codes, levels offered
- **File E**: Student enrolment data — individual student records

**Form TL (Teacher Load)**: Summary of how many hours each teacher teaches per week, broken down by subject. This is for school reference only — NOT submitted to DES. EduPod's timetabling data makes this a trivial auto-generation.

#### B. DTR Returns (Deployment of Teaching Resources)

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **What** | Subject code management — sync with DES subject code master list |
| **When** | Alongside September Returns |
| **Purpose** | Ensures school's subject offerings match DES's canonical subject code list |

#### C. October Returns / Annual Census

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **Legal basis** | Education Act 1998 |
| **Who** | All primary (via POD) and post-primary (via P-POD) schools |
| **When** | Annually, cutoff date is September 30th (or preceding Friday). Submitted by ~7 October |
| **What** | Total enrolment snapshot: individual student records with PPSN, demographics, enrolment status |
| **Impact** | Directly determines teaching posts, funding, capitation grants. Delayed submission = delayed grant payments |
| **Validation** | Schools must run a "Rules Report" to identify and fix errors. Submissions with unresolved errors are rejected |

---

### 1.2 P-POD — Post-Primary Online Database

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **Legal basis** | DES mandate for all post-primary schools |
| **System** | Central database accessed via Esinet secure portal |
| **Data collected** | PPSN, name, address, DOB, gender, nationality, mother's maiden name, mother tongue, ethnic/cultural background, religion (with parental written consent) |
| **Key functions** | Teacher allocation, school funding, State Examinations Commission data |
| **Integration methods** | Manual entry via Esinet, Excel template upload, or **automated sync from approved school management software** |
| **CBA results** | Junior Cycle Classroom-Based Assessment results uploaded via P-POD for JCPA (Junior Cycle Profile of Achievement) |

**Competitor benchmark:**
- **VSware**: Full automated P-POD sync, 400+ schools, 10+ years battle-tested
- **Compass**: Automated daily P-POD sync including CBA uploads
- **What EduPod needs**: Contact `ppodhelpdesk@education.gov.ie` for integration specs (shared with approved vendors)

---

### 1.3 POD — Primary Online Database

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **Who** | All primary schools |
| **System** | Nationwide individualised database of all primary school pupils |
| **Purpose** | Annual census, teacher allocation, capitation grants, pupil register, tracking pupils primary → post-primary |
| **Submission** | Annual October census via POD |
| **Competitor** | Aladdin has ~90% primary market share with deep POD integration |

> [!NOTE]
> POD is lower priority if targeting post-primary first, but essential for primary market entry. The primary market is heavily defended by Aladdin.

---

### 1.4 Tusla — Education Welfare Reporting

The most operationally impactful regulatory area. Under the **Education (Welfare) Act 2000**, schools have multiple reporting obligations to Tusla's Education Support Service (TESS):

#### A. Student Absence Reports (SAR)

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **Threshold** | Students aged 6–16 who accumulate **20+ days of absence** |
| **Frequency** | Twice per year |
| **Period 1** | Start of term → Christmas break. Submit promptly after Christmas |
| **Period 2** | Christmas → end of school year. Submit ASAP after schools close |
| **Submission** | Electronic via `portal.tusla.ie` |
| **Absence categories** | Illness, Urgent family reason, Holiday, Suspension, Other, Unexplained |
| **Rule** | Students with fewer than 20 days absence must NOT be included |

#### B. Annual Attendance Report (AAR)

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **Who** | Every recognised school |
| **When** | Within 6 weeks of school year end |
| **Coverage** | **All students** (including under-6 and over-16), excluding PLC/adult education |
| **Content** | Total days lost to absence, total students absent 20+ days, total suspensions, total expulsions |

#### C. Additional Mandatory Notifications

| Notification | Trigger | Requirement |
|-------------|---------|-------------|
| **Suspension** | ≥6 consecutive school days | Notify TESS of each occurrence |
| **Expulsion** | Any | Notify TESS immediately |
| **Reduced School Day** | Any student on reduced timetable | Report to TESS (since Jan 2022) |
| **Educational Welfare Referral** | Principal has concerns after in-school interventions | Submit to TESS. Deadlines: May 2 (post-primary), May 30 (primary) |

**What this means for EduPod:**
- EduPod already has sophisticated attendance + pattern detection + 20-day-style threshold alerting
- Needs: Tusla-specific absence code mapping, SAR export format, AAR generation, suspension/expulsion/reduced day tracking + notifications, referral workflow
- The threshold dashboard ("students approaching 20 days") is a natural extension of existing pattern alerts

---

### 1.5 Children First / Child Safeguarding

| Legislation | Requirement |
|-------------|-------------|
| **Children First Act 2015** | All schools must have a **Child Safeguarding Statement** (written declaration + risk assessment). Reviewed annually |
| **Mandated reporting** | All registered teachers are **mandated persons** — must report concerns to Tusla via their DLP |
| **DLP** | Board appoints a **Designated Liaison Person** and Deputy DLP as child safeguarding contacts |
| **Reporting chain** | Teacher → DLP → joint assessment → mandated report to Tusla if threshold met |

**EduPod already has:** Safeguarding module with Tusla/Garda referrals and sealed records in the Behaviour module. This is largely covered but should surface in the Regulatory Portal for compliance visibility.

---

### 1.6 Anti-Bullying — Bí Cineálta (From September 2025)

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **Legal basis** | Circular 0055/2024, replacing 2013 procedures |
| **Effective** | September 1, 2025 |
| **New requirements** | All bullying incidents must be recorded; Principal provides update at **every** Board meeting; annual report to DES; annual policy review |
| **Extended scope** | Gender identity bullying, cyberbullying, racist bullying, sexist bullying, sexual harassment |

**What this means for EduPod:** The Behaviour module already handles incident recording. Needs: bullying-specific categorisation, Board meeting report generation, annual DES submission format, and compliance dashboard tracking.

---

### 1.7 FSSU — Financial Governance

The **Financial Support Services Unit** enforces financial accountability for all school Boards of Management:

| Obligation | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Annual accounts** | Submit via FSSU Online Accounts Reporting System. Due by February 28. Year ends August 31. Standardised chart of accounts |
| **OLCS** | Online Claims System — for DES grant claims. Requires segregation of duties (data entry ≠ approval) |
| **Monthly reporting** | FSSU provides templates for monthly financial reports to Board |
| **Charities Regulator** | Schools must also report as registered charities |
| **CSO** | Central Statistics Office reporting |

**EduPod opportunity:** Finance module already handles invoicing, payments, and financial reporting. An FSSU export wizard that maps EduPod's chart of accounts to FSSU's standardised format would be a significant time-saver.

---

### 1.8 DES Inspectorate — Whole School Evaluation

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **Framework** | "Looking at Our School 2022" quality framework |
| **Inspection types** | WSE-MLL (Whole School Evaluation – Management, Leadership and Learning) |
| **What inspectors examine** | Quality of teaching/learning, management, leadership, School Self-Evaluation (SSE) process, implementation of prior recommendations |
| **Data requirements** | Schools must demonstrate SSE engagement and data analysis to inform planning |
| **Reports** | Published on gov.ie after inspection |

**What this means for EduPod:** Schools need easy access to aggregated data across all modules (attendance trends, grade distributions, behaviour analytics, SEN provision) to demonstrate data-informed decision-making during inspections. A "WSE Preparation Pack" that auto-generates the key metrics inspectors look for would be a huge differentiator.

---

### 1.9 SEN / NCSE / NEPS

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **SET allocation** | Special Education Teacher hours allocated by NCSE based on: complex learning needs (68.5%), enrolment (25%), disadvantage (6.5%). No medical diagnosis required |
| **SNA allocation** | NCSE Toolkit for SNA deployment — identify, plan, deploy, review cycle |
| **SET review** | Schools can apply to NCSE for review if allocation is insufficient |
| **Forward Planning** | Circular 0080/2024 — NCSE access to school waiting lists for specialist placements |
| **NEPS** | Educational psychological services — consultative model, continuum-based assessment |

**What this means for EduPod:** Schools need to track SEN provision per student (learning support plans, SET hours used, SNA assignments) and generate the data required for NCSE allocation reviews. Phase 1 Expansion-B already targets SEN — this is a confirmation of its necessity.

---

### 1.10 GDPR / Data Protection

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **Legal basis** | GDPR, Data Protection Acts 2018 |
| **DPC Toolkit** | Data Protection Commissioner published a "Data Protection Toolkit for Schools" |
| **SARs** | Subject Access Requests — 1 month response time (school holidays do NOT extend this) |
| **Children's data** | Age-specific rules: primary = parents can request; post-primary <16 = parental + child consent; 17+ = student's own request |
| **Records of processing** | Schools must document all data categories, legal basis, retention periods |
| **Third-party processors** | School management systems must provide GDPR guarantees (Article 28) |

**EduPod already has:** GDPR compliance module with SARs, erasure, rectification, and audit logging. The Regulatory Portal should surface GDPR compliance status as a dashboard widget.

---

### 1.11 SEAI — Energy Reporting

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **Legal basis** | Statutory Instrument 426 of 2014 |
| **Climate target** | 51% reduction in GHG emissions, 50% energy efficiency improvement by 2030 |
| **Reporting** | Annual submission to SEAI M&R-2030 system |
| **Data required** | Contact details, school size (pupils, staff, floor area), annual energy consumption (electricity, gas, oil, LPG, diesel), energy management commentary, energy-saving projects |
| **Deadline** | Annual cycle, late submissions not accepted |

**EduPod opportunity:** Basic data entry + reminder system. Low complexity but demonstrates comprehensive compliance coverage. Could potentially auto-populate staff/student counts from EduPod data.

---

### 1.12 Education (Admission to Schools) Act 2018

| Obligation | Detail |
|-----------|--------|
| **Annual Admissions Notice** | Must publish on school website ≥1 week before accepting applications. Includes: places available, application dates, decision timeline, prior year stats |
| **Admissions policy** | Must be publicly available |
| **Timeline rules** | Cannot accept applications before October 1st of preceding year. Process must be open ≥3 weeks |
| **Waiting lists** | Must be phased out by January 31, 2025 |
| **Code of Behaviour** | Must be published; parents must confirm acceptance |
| **Data sharing** | Section 66(6) allows BoM-to-BoM sharing of admitted student lists |

**EduPod already has:** Admissions module with configurable forms, application pipeline, and public application submission. Needs: Annual Admissions Notice generation, compliance timeline tracking, prior year stats auto-generation.

---

### 1.13 Wellbeing Framework

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **Framework** | "Wellbeing Policy Statement and Framework for Practice" (2018) |
| **Requirement** | All schools must embed a Self-Evaluation Wellbeing Promotion Process |
| **Areas** | Child-centred approach, equitable opportunities, whole-school support, outcomes-focused practice, early intervention |
| **Reporting** | School Self-Evaluation (SSE) process — review, develop, implement, track impact |
| **Junior Cycle** | Wellbeing reported as "Other Area of Learning" on JCPA |

---

### 1.14 Junior Cycle — CBA / SLAR / JCPA (Post-Primary Only)

| Aspect | Detail |
|--------|--------|
| **CBAs** | 2 per subject (2nd and 3rd year). Descriptors: Exceptional / Above expectations / In line with expectations / Yet to meet expectations |
| **SLAR** | Subject Learning and Assessment Review meetings — teacher moderation for consistency |
| **JCPA** | Junior Cycle Profile of Achievement — combines exam results, CBA results, wellbeing reporting |
| **P-POD integration** | CBA results uploaded to P-POD. Specific P-POD User Guide for "JCPA 2024" available |
| **Reporting** | Schools must manage CBA data and upload finalised assessments to P-POD by deadline |

**EduPod connection:** The Gradebook module already handles assessment management. Needs: CBA-specific assessment type, SLAR meeting workflow, JCPA data generation, P-POD CBA upload format.

